# Browser targets for SWC downlevel-compile (NOT for Next.js polyfills).
#
# What this actually controls:
# - SWC's `target` for the bundle output (modern syntax kept, no ES5
#   transpilation of native async/await, optional chaining, etc.).
# - Tailwind / autoprefixer / cssnano vendor-prefix output.
#
# What this does NOT control (counter-intuitively):
# - The contents of `polyfills-*.js`. Next.js 15 polyfills are gated by
#   the framework's own baseline target and shipped regardless of
#   browserslist. After F0 + F1 the polyfills-*.js hash and size were
#   unchanged — verified by direct measurement. See
#   `docs/BUGFIX_LESSONS.md#2026-05-25` for the investigation.
#
# Why keep this file then:
# - SWC downlevel-target IS browserslist-driven. A narrower target lets
#   SWC keep more modern syntax in shipped JS, which is slightly smaller
#   and parses slightly faster than transpiled ES5/ES2015.
# - Tailwind purge + autoprefixer use it.
# - Setting an honest target avoids the "what minimum browsers do we
#   actually support?" question becoming undefined behaviour.
#
# Targets reflect Telegram WebView reality:
# - Telegram iOS: Safari 14+ (iOS 14+ required for current Telegram).
# - Telegram Android: system Chrome WebView, typically 90+ on supported
#   Android versions.
# - Telegram Desktop: Chromium-based, modern.
#
# DO NOT also set `browserslist` in `apps/web/package.json` — browserslist
# refuses to load with two sources present (defensive throw). Local
# `pnpm -C apps/web build` will fail with a clear error if you add both.

iOS >= 14
Safari >= 14
Chrome >= 90
ChromeAndroid >= 90
Edge >= 90
Firefox >= 90
